000 and 2001. The year after that, he went on to serve as Western Cape premier. The FF+ has seen big gains in the 2019 polls. It is set to become the fifth largest political party in the National Assembly with 2.3% of the vote. The party’s leadership estimates it will be allocated between eight and 12 seats in Parliament. Marais said he is ready to take a seat on the national stage if asked to do so by his party. Another veteran politician could also make her return to national politics is former Cape Town mayor and DA member, Patricia de Lille. De Lille also campaigned for the Premiership in the province. Her party — GOOD — secured 3% of the vote in the provincial poll. But Brett Herron,  the party’s secretary general, said with more than 66 000 votes nationally, GOOD is expected to be allocated one seat in the National Assembly. “I think it’s likely she will go to national, and then I will be in the provincial legislature,” Herron said.